tion and makes the case that philosophy for Cicero was not a retreat from politics but a continuation of politics by other means, an alternative way of living a political life and serving the state under newly restricted conditions. Baraz examines the rhetorical battle that Cicero stages in his philosophical prefaces--a battle between the forces that would oppose or support his project. He presents his philosophy as intimately connected to the new political circumstances and his exclusion from politics. His goal--to benefit the state by providing new moral resources for the Roman elite--was traditional, even if his method of translating Greek philosophical knowledge into Latin and combining Greek sources with Roman heritage was unorthodox. A Written Republic provides a new perspective on Cicero's conception of his philosophical project while also adding to the broader picture of late-Roman political, intellectual, and cultural life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAcademic Skepticism.  aBellum Catilinae.  aBellum Iugurthinum.  aCato the Younger.  aCicero.  aDe Divinatione.  aDe Finibus.  aDe Natura Deorum.  aDe Officiis.  aDe Senectute.  aEnnius.  aJulius Caesar.  aMarcus the Younger.  aParadoxa Stoicorum.  aQuintus Cicero.  aRhetorica ad Herennium.  aRoman elite.  aSallust.  aTopica.  aTullia.  aTusculan Disputations.  aaction.  aamicitia.  acharacter.  acivil war.  acultural life.  adedicatees.  adictatorship.  aintellectual activity.  aintellectual life.  alate Roman republic.  aletters.  amos maiorum.  anegotium.  aoratory.  aotium.  apatriotism.  aphilosophical writings.  aphilosophy.  apolitical life.  apolitics.  aprefaces.  apublic life.  areaders.  arhetoric.  a